a real-life situation, the
highly encrypted
message sent to bombers,
submarines and missile

33:36.181 --> 33:42.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crews would tell them which war
plan to execute
and which targets to destroy.

33:42.988 --> 33:49.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The coded message echoes,
because it's sent
by many different radios around
the world,

33:49.261 --> 33:54.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to ensure that even if the
nation were under
nuclear attack, at least one of
the messages

33:54.532 --> 33:58.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would get through.

33:58.970 --> 34:03.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The "NewsHour" was granted rare
access to
America's nuclear war fighters
over the past

34:03.375 --> 34:08.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
six months. At Minot Air Force
base in North
Dakota, we spent the day with
the airmen who

34:08.747 --> 34:14.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
load the B-52 bombers and the
crews that fly
them.

34:14.719 --> 34:18.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chief Master Sergeant Lee Robins
is the wing
weapons manager.

34:18.456 --> 34:20.292 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How can you tell how old it is?

34:20.325 --> 34:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHIEF MASTER SGT. LEE ROBINS,
U.S. Air Force:
It's pretty easy. So, there is
-- on the tail

34:24.596 --> 34:29.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
number, if we look underneath
the letters
A.F., this is a 61, so that is
when it rolled

34:29.067 --> 34:30.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
off the assembly line.

34:30.869 --> 34:35.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: That makes this
aircraft 19
years older than Major Luke
Dellenbach, a

34:35.540 --> 34:37.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
B-52 commander and instructor
pilot.

34:37.542 --> 34:42.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I asked him about the
differences between
flying a conventional vs.
nuclear mission.

34:42.914 --> 34:46.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAJ. LUKE DELLENBACH, U.S. Air
Force: For
a nuclear mission for us, it's
very controlled.

34:46.151 --> 34:50.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's very scripted. The
president doesn't
want us doing things that we
want to do. There

34:50.922 --> 34:54.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is not inventiveness. It's very
much you follow
the rules and you follow the
procedures and

34:54.826 --> 34:56.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
guidelines that we have.

34:56.628 --> 35:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For conventional, it's almost
the opposite.
We have a lot more flexibility.
We can be

35:01.299 --> 35:04.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more innovative. We can hit
targets different
ways.

35:04.369 --> 35:09.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: It's a sobering
mission, and
the venerable B-52 has been
updated with modern

35:09.374 --> 35:15.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
avionics to carry it out, even
though, as
the crew is quick to show us,
some non-mission-critical

35:15.480 --> 35:19.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
systems are an antiquated
reminder of its
Cold War history.

35:19.184 --> 35:20.952 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What do we have?

35:20.986 --> 35:21.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAJ. C. RYAN COX, U.S. Air
Force: So, over
here, we have the oven. It has
two different

35:21.686 --> 35:22.487 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
settings, off and 400 degrees.

35:22.520 --> 35:24.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: 1960s
technology?

35:24.289 --> 35:25.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAJ. C. RYAN COX: It still works
today. And
up here, we have a sextant port
(INAUDIBLE)

35:25.757 --> 35:28.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
navigation if everything else
fails.

35:28.460 --> 35:33.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: You know how to
use a sextant?

35:33.365 --> 35:43.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAJ. C. RYAN COX: No. We usually
put a GPS
antenna out of it if we need it.

35:43.174 --> 35:45.110 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:45.143 --> 35:51.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: While bombers
crews typically
fly at 50,000 feet above the
ground, the submariners

35:51.616 --> 35:56.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we visited last summer lurk
hundreds of feet
below the surface, in this case
plying the

35:56.688 --> 35:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
depths of the Pacific Ocean.

35:58.957 --> 36:01.793 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MAN: Dive, dive.

36:01.826 --> 36:07.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: By far, the
stealthiest leg
of the nuclear triad, the
submarine's unofficial

36:07.932 --> 36:10.502 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
motto is hide with pride.

36:10.535 --> 36:16.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The USS Pennsylvania's crew
spends three months
at a time in the cramped
confines of the windowless

36:16.374 --> 36:22.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ballistic missile submarine,
breathing recycled
air and never seeing the sun,
that is, unless

36:22.647 --> 36:28.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they are among the chosen few
who get to go
topside while the sub takes on
provisions,

36:28.053 --> 36:33.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
an elaborate and highly
choreographed ritual
on the high seas in which canvas
bags of food

36:33.792 --> 36:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an supplies are transferred from
boat to boat.

36:37.162 --> 36:43.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the subs patrol undersea,
missileers
serve underground. They have to
take an elevator

36:43.568 --> 36:49.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
50 to 60 feet down each time
they arrive at
their jobs. There are 45 launch
facilities

36:49.607 --> 36:56.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spread across the America's
heartland controlling
the intercontinental ballistic
missiles, ICBM,

36:56.114 --> 36:58.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
buried in silos in fixed, known
locations.

36:58.683 --> 37:00.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Incoming emergency action
message.

37:00.552 --> 37:06.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: We got to watch
two junior
officers practicing running
through the lengthy

37:06.057 --> 37:08.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
checklist to launch nuclear
missiles.

37:08.860 --> 37:15.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To get the launch keys, they
must each unlock
a padlock. In this training
scenario, using

37:15.467 --> 37:22.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unfamiliar locks, a forgotten
combination
delays a mock launch. In case
you're wondering,

37:22.440 --> 37:27.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
missileers can't just go rogue.
It takes four
officers, in two separate launch
facilities,

37:27.712 --> 37:33.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to launch a missile after an
authentication
code is received.

37:33.818 --> 37:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't help noticing how
young America's
nuclear warriors are. First
Lieutenant Kathleen

37:38.756 --> 37:45.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fosterling who commands a
two-person missile
combat crew, is 27. She works a
24-hour shift

37:45.530 --> 37:49.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
eight times a month, waiting for
an order
she hopes to never receive.

37:49.234 --> 37:53.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1ST LT. KATHLEEN FOSTERLING,
U.S. Air Force:
I wouldn't say it's lonely. Yes,
we only work

37:53.338 --> 37:58.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with technically one other
person, but we
have all the other guys topside.
We have -- we

37:58.243 --> 38:02.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talk to the other crews at the
other capsules
constantly.

38:02.714 --> 38:06.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But our free time, if we have
any, not always
-- sometimes, there is a lot --
sometimes,

38:06.417 --> 38:13.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is not -- a lot of people
do homework.
There is a lot of people in
school. We read.

38:13.091 --> 38:19.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We watch TV. We watch movies,
hang out with
each other. It's not so bad.

38:19.564 --> 38:21.332 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:21.366 --> 38:26.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Do you ever
wonder, we ask,
what it would be like if she had
to turn the

38:26.104 --> 38:27.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
launch key for real?

38:27.872 --> 38:29.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1ST LT. KATHLEEN FOSTERLING:
It's hard to
think about it, because you
don't know what

38:29.874 --> 38:35.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is going to happen in that
situation. You
just have to do your job. And
whatever the

38:35.246 --> 38:38.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
outcome is, it is.

38:38.082 --> 38:43.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: First Lieutenant
Fosterling
is not alone. A number of
nuclear warriors

38:43.588 --> 38:48.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
told us it's very hard to think
about what
it would be like after the
unthinkable happens.

38:48.760 --> 38:52.497 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Now Jamie McIntyre
joins us.

38:52.530 --> 38:57.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Jamie, this was really a
remarkable series.
You showed us things that we
rarely see on

38:57.835 --> 38:59.671 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
television.

38:59.704 --> 39:03.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have to ask you, what do you
take away from
this personally? What was most
memorable for

39:03.775 --> 39:05.543 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you?

39:05.577 --> 39:07.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Well, you know,
John, one
of the things we asked almost
all the people

39:07.345 --> 39:10.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we interviewed was, have you
ever thought
about what would happen if you
actually had

39:10.648 --> 39:14.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to employ these weapons? It is
the classic
unthinkable scenario.

39:14.986 --> 39:18.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we found was that, yes,
most of them
had thought about it, but they
don't dwell

39:18.756 --> 39:23.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on it. These are military people
trained to
a mission and they think about
their part

39:23.428 --> 39:28.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the mission, and there's not
a whole lot
of angst of what would happen if
they actually

39:28.833 --> 39:31.336 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were involved in an all-out
nuclear exchange.

39:31.369 --> 39:35.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was interesting. When we
talked to the
submarine commander, we said,
well, how would

39:35.206 --> 39:39.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you deal with the crew after you
have already
launched all these missiles and
you know that

39:39.177 --> 39:43.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
maybe even the end of the world
is coming?
And he said, well, it would be
difficult.

39:43.214 --> 39:45.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Hopefully, he said, there will
be some guidance.

39:45.984 --> 39:50.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: A little guidance
from the Pentagon
on it.

39:50.154 --> 39:55.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And talk about that, because
this really is
-- they are handling the awesome
power of

39:55.493 --> 40:00.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nuclear weapons. But it's a job
for them.
It's their assignment. It's
their day-to-day

40:00.832 --> 40:02.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
assignment.

40:02.634 --> 40:04.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Well, I
mentioned this in
the piece, that one of the
things that really

40:04.269 --> 40:08.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
struck me was how young
everybody was, and
how they're focused on their
mission.

40:08.906 --> 40:16.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The young 1st lieutenant that we
met in the
missile silo, 1st Lieutenant
Kathleen Fosterling,

40:16.648 --> 40:20.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so she's very young and she's
commanding this
two-person crew, but yet -- and
she's in this

40:20.385 --> 40:25.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tiny room underground in a
windowless room
every day. And one of the things
that struck

40:25.757 --> 40:29.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you is that you had the -- you
see how they
personalize their life.

40:29.127 --> 40:34.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for instance, those locks --
and you saw
the sequence in the story where
the training

40:34.866 --> 40:38.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scenario, they can't get the
lock open because
they're using a training lock.
In real life,

40:38.469 --> 40:43.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they all use their own personal
padlocks.
And she had plastered hers with
Hello Kitty

40:43.141 --> 40:47.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stickers, which seemed to be
sort of this
juxtaposition of the fact that
they're -- they're

40:47.845 --> 40:52.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conducting this awesome mission,
but, at the
same time, it is a job, and they
just need

40:52.150 --> 40:56.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to have some sort of human
interaction and
think of it as something that
they just do

40:56.421 --> 40:57.388 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
every day.

40:57.422 --> 40:59.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Just personalizing
their workspace.

40:59.157 --> 41:03.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jamie McIntyre, remarkable
reporting. Thank
you very much.

41:03.061 --> 41:09.767 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Thank you.

41:09.801 --> 41:18.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: India has the
world's largest
number of people, about 76
million, without

41:18.209 --> 41:23.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
access to clean drinking water.
And that's
according to a report the
international charity

41:23.314 --> 41:25.416 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WaterAid released last month.

41:25.450 --> 41:30.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro
reports, an innovative solution
to that problem

41:30.888 --> 41:33.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is popping up across the
country.

41:33.324 --> 41:35.893 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
His report is part of our
Breakthrough series.

41:35.927 --> 41:42.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The United
Nations estimates
that women in India spend a
collective 150

41:42.900 --> 41:49.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
million workdays every year just
gathering
water, water that's increasingly
scarce and

41:49.340 --> 41:51.109 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
polluted.

41:51.142 --> 41:56.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, in parts of the country,
including this
Delhi suburb, an experiment is
under way.

41:56.214 --> 42:03.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's called a water ATM.
Customers purchase
credit on a prepaid card, scan
it at the tap,

42:03.821 --> 42:08.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and out comes water that's drawn
from the
ground and purified right at the
site, using

42:08.893 --> 42:11.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a technology called reverse
osmosis.

42:11.596 --> 42:17.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amit Mishra manages the Delhi
facilities for
a social business called
Sarvajal, which hopes

42:17.535 --> 42:22.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to use reinvest profits it makes
to sustain
these outlets over the long
term.

42:22.573 --> 42:26.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This where the water gets
purified. It goes
into the large tanks here
storage?

42:26.978 --> 42:28.679 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMIT MISHRA, Sarvajal: Yes.

42:28.713 --> 42:33.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: With
charitable grants
for the $30,000 of equipment and
land given

42:33.084 --> 42:38.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
by the local government,
Sarvajal can charge
customers a fraction of the
price of commercially

42:38.456 --> 42:42.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bottled water, which most people
here cannot
afford.

42:42.860 --> 42:48.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fetching water remains a mostly
female chore.
It's still self-service with
heavy lifting.

42:48.433 --> 42:53.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's a massive improvement
over what most
of Delhi's poorer neighborhoods
have.

42:53.171 --> 42:54.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): By
12:00?

42:54.705 --> 42:58.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: We filmed
their ordeal
six years ago.

42:58.676 --> 43:00.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): By
4:00.

43:00.645 --> 43:06.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The long
wait for a municipal
tanker truck that has no fixed
schedule, the

43:06.851 --> 43:12.957 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
mad dash when it finally
arrives.

43:12.990 --> 43:18.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The city's middle class buys its
way out of
such chaos. Jyoti Sharme lives
in an apartment

43:18.629 --> 43:23.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's hooked up to the city
water supply,
better off, but hardly well off.

43:23.534 --> 43:25.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JYOTI SHARME, India: We get
water 45 minutes
a day in the morning, and that's
it.

43:25.970 --> 43:27.371 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: From the
city?

43:27.405 --> 43:30.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JYOTI SHARME: Yes, into these
storage tanks.

43:30.274 --> 43:34.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: She
described an elaborate
jury-rigged system of pumps or
motors homeowners

43:34.979 --> 43:38.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
use to extract water from the
aging city pipes.

43:38.382 --> 43:42.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JYOTI SHARME: These are all
pipelines made
by the people themselves. And
these motors,

43:42.787 --> 43:50.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they actually create a suction
vacuum. So,
if there is no water in the
pipeline, any

43:50.495 --> 43:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crack in the pipe will allow
sewer or dirty
water to get into the pipelines.

43:54.866 --> 44:00.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And things
have hardly
improved for most people since
our 2010 visit.

44:00.471 --> 44:06.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
K.H. PATIL, State Legislator: In
India, every
