47:35.219 --> 47:41.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chef Jacques Pepin arrived in
the United States
from France in 1959. He is the
author of the

47:41.225 --> 47:47.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
widely cited French culinary
text book "La
Technique," the star of several
PBS cooking

47:47.732 --> 47:52.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shows, including one with his
friend and fellow
cook the late Julia Child.

47:52.603 --> 47:56.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, Pepin shares his idea
on the essence
of a recipe.

47:56.640 --> 48:02.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUES PEPIN, Chef: For someone
who writes
recipes, there is a paradox
between the written

48:02.313 --> 48:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
recipe and the creation of a
taste.

48:05.983 --> 48:11.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When writing a recipe, one
records a moment
in time which can never be
duplicated exactly

48:11.622 --> 48:18.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
again. The paradox is that the
recipe tells
the reader, this must be done
this way, when,

48:18.462 --> 48:25.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in fact, to get the result
you're looking
for, the recipe has to be
modified each time.

48:25.469 --> 48:31.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The exact reproduction of a
taste, which is
what the making of a dish is,
only works when

48:31.542 --> 48:36.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the processes, timing, and
ingredients are
adjusted and changed to fit each
particular

48:36.347 --> 48:38.182 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
situation.

48:38.215 --> 48:44.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a gap between the
step-by-step procedure
and the completed dish, just as
an artist

48:44.855 --> 48:49.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cannot equate the technical
process of painting
with the finished work of art.

48:49.460 --> 48:56.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Several years ago, I wrote a
recipe for pears
in caramel sauce. The idea was,
you peel the

48:56.033 --> 49:00.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pears, cut them in half, remove
the seeds,
sprinkle them with sugar, and
place them in

49:00.504 --> 49:06.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a very hot oven. Exposed to the
heat, the
juice of the pear seeps out,
combines with

49:06.076 --> 49:09.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the sugar and creates a caramel.
By then,
the pears are cooked.

49:10.014 --> 49:15.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Add cream to the caramel, and
the resulting
sauce is poured around the pear
in a serving

49:15.186 --> 49:21.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dish. As the sauce cools and
thickens, it
is finished with a bit of pear
brandy or cognac.

49:21.659 --> 49:28.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I first created this
recipe, the pears
were done in 30 minutes. That
amount of time

49:28.165 --> 49:34.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
only reflects the unique set of
circumstances
I faced, ripeness of the pear,
type of roasting

49:34.772 --> 49:39.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
pan I used. This is what
happened on that
particular day.

49:39.977 --> 49:45.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The next time, I used pears that
were more
ripe, and they were done in 10
minutes. But

49:45.683 --> 49:51.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
