50:16.213 --> 50:23.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the recipe had been followed
to the letter,
the finished dish would have
been a disaster,

50:23.087 --> 50:29.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but understanding the idea in
the platonic
sense behind the dish enables
the cook to

50:29.059 --> 50:31.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
adjust and compensate for
ingredients, temperature,
humidity, et cetera.

50:31.829 --> 50:42.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what is the point of at
recipe? A recipe
is a teaching tool, a guide, a
point of departure.

50:42.806 --> 50:47.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have to follow it exactly
the first time
you make the dish. But as you
make it again

50:47.811 --> 50:53.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and again, you will change it,
you will massage
it to fit your own taste, your
own sense of

50:53.651 --> 50:55.419 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
aesthetic.

50:55.452 --> 50:59.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have had dinner many times at
the home of
friends who cooked from one of
my cookbooks

50:59.857 --> 51:05.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and have often been amazed at
how far away
the dish has moved from the
original recipe.

51:05.496 --> 51:13.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it is not necessarily a
negative experience.
In fact, it is sometimes better
than the original.

51:13.337 --> 51:23.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I end up getting credit and
thanks for
a dish that has nothing to do
